FDTD predicts the performance of antenna as a EMI sensor in receiving mode very easily and accurately. Measurement of EM field in the near-field region of a source using far-field CAF always introduces some error. When the distance between the source and receiver varies the CAF is also change. The CAF in near-field region is a function of the distance between source and the receiver and also depends upon the type of source. When the size of the ground plane of a monopole changes, it effects on the CAF of the monopole but it is not as much vertical reflector effects. Due to the reflector, the CAF is changed and formed some ripple. For larger reflector the ripples are more than the small one and it is more in higher frequency region. So, from this study it is concluded that vertically reflecting walls effect much more in EMI measurements than the horizontal ground plane. 

